# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aiken-county-south-carolina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The **1880 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office during June 1880, was the tenth United States census.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] It was the first time that women were permitted to be enumerators.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The Superintendent of the Census was Francis Amasa Walker.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York City—recorded a population of over one million, and the first census in which the 20 most populated cities all recorded over 100,000 residents.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Schedule 4 (Social statistics) was the responsibility of experts and special agents, rather than the enumerators.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The majority of the data came from correspondence with officials of institutions providing care and treatment of certain members of the population.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Experts and special agents also were employed to collect data on valuation, taxation, and indebtedness; religion and libraries; colleges, academies, and schools; newspapers and periodicals, and wages.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1880 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series, which contains microdata.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau; after which the original sheets were transferred to various state archives, libraries, or universities.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The microfilmed census is available in rolls from the National Archives and Records Administration.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, along which digital indices.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1880 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census determined the resident population of the United States to be 50,189,209, an increase of 30.2 percent over the 38,555,983 persons enumerated during the 1870 census.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The mean center of United States population for 1880 was in Boone County, Kentucky.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The results from the census were used to determine the apportionment for the 48th, 49th, 50th, 51st, and 52nd sessions of the United States Congress.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The processing of the 1880 census data took so long (eight years) that the Census Bureau contracted Herman Hollerith to design and build a tabulating machine to be used for the next census.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1880-united-states-census] The 1880 census also led to the discovery of the Alabama paradox.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The **1890 United States census** was taken beginning June 2, 1890.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The census determined the resident population of the United States to be 62,979,766, an increase of 25.5 percent over the 50,189,209 persons enumerated during the 1880 census.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The data reported that the distribution of the population had resulted in the disappearance of the American frontier.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a majority of states recorded populations of over one million and the first in which three cities, New York City, Chicago, and Philadelphia, recorded populations of over one million.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The census also saw Chicago rise in rank to the nation's second-most populous city, a position it would hold until Los Angeles, the 57th-most populous city as of 1890, supplanted it in 1990.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] This was the first U.S. census to use machines to tabulate the collected data.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Most of the 1890 census materials were destroyed on January 10, 1921, when the Commerce Department building caught fire, and in the subsequent disposal of the remaining damaged records.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census was the first to be compiled using methods invented by Herman Hollerith and was overseen by Superintendents Robert P.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Data was entered on a machine readable medium (punched cards) and tabulated by machine.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Changes from the 1880 census included the larger population, the number of data items to be collected from individuals, the Census Bureau headcount, the volume of scheduled publications, and the use of Hollerith's electromechanical tabulators.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The net effect of these changes was to reduce the time required to process the census from eight years for the 1880 census to six years for the 1890 census.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The total population of 62,947,714, the family, or *rough*, count, was announced after only six weeks of processing (punched cards were not used for this tabulation).
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The public reaction to this tabulation was disbelief, as it was widely believed that the "right answer" was at least 75,000,000.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The United States census of 1890 showed a total of 248,253 Native Americans living in the United States, down from 400,764 Native Americans identified in the census of 1850.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The 1890 census announced that the frontier region of the United States no longer existed, and that the Census Bureau would no longer track the westward migration of the U.S. population.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] In practice, however, said migration can still be tracked by plotting each succeeding census' mean center of United States population.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] By 1890, settlement in the American West had reached sufficient population density that the frontier line had disappeared.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The original data for the 1890 census is mostly unavailable.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The population schedules were damaged in a fire in the basement of the U.S.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Department of Commerce building in Washington, D.C. in 1921.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Some 25% of the materials were presumed destroyed and another 50% damaged by smoke and water, although the actual damage may have been closer to 15–25%.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The damage to the records led to an outcry for a permanent National Archives.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] In December 1932, following standard federal record-keeping procedures, the Chief Clerk of the Bureau of the Census sent the Librarian of Congress a list of papers to be destroyed, including the original 1890 census schedules.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] The Librarian was asked by the Bureau to identify any records which should be retained for historical purposes, but the Librarian did not accept the census records.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Congress authorized destruction of that list of records on February 21, 1933, and the surviving original 1890 census records were destroyed by government order by 1934 or 1935.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1890-united-states-census] Few sets of microdata from the 1890 census survive.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1892-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1892 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 8, 1892, as part of the 1892 United States presidential election.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1892-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Voters chose nine representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1892-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina voted for the Democratic nominee, former President Grover Cleveland, who was running for a second, non-consecutive term, over Republican nominee, incumbent President Benjamin Harrison.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1892-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Cleveland won the state by a landslide margin of 58.60%.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1892-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The three counties that voted Republican were all majority black.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1892-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] This was the last election before the disfranchising 1895 state constitutional convention.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1896 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 3, 1896, as part of the 1896 United States presidential election.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina overwhelmingly voted for the Democratic nominee, former U.S.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Representative from Nebraska William Jennings Bryan, over the Republican nominee, former governor of Ohio William McKinley.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Bryan won the state by a landslide margin of 71.79%.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] However, McKinley's performance would actually prove to be a high water mark for Republicans going into the 20th century; he was the last Republican to win even 10% of the state's vote until Dwight D.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] With 85.3% of the popular vote, South Carolina would prove to be Bryan's second strongest state in the 1896 presidential election only after Mississippi.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] This election marked the end of Reconstruction in South Carolina, following the 1895 state constitutional convention that disenfranchised African Americans in South Carolina.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The multiple-ballot box law was challenged in court.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] On May 8, 1895, Judge Nathan Goff of the United States Circuit Court declared the provision unconstitutional and enjoined the state from taking further action under it.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] But in June 1895, the US Fourth Circuit Court of Appeals reversed Goff and dissolved the injunction, leaving the way open for a convention.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The constitutional convention met on September 10 and adjourned on December 4, 1895.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] By the new constitution, South Carolina adopted the Mississippi Plan until January 1, 1898.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Any male citizen could be registered who was able to read a section of the constitution or to satisfy the election officer that he understood it when read to him.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Those thus registered were to remain voters for life.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1896-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Bryan would later defeat McKinley in South Carolina again four years later and would win the state again in 1908 against William Howard Taft.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] The **1900 United States census**, conducted by the Census Office on June 1, 1900, determined the resident population of the United States to be 76,212,168, an increase of 21.01% from the 62,979,766 persons enumerated during the 1890 census.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] It was the last census to be conducted before the founding of the permanent United States Census Bureau.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] The census saw the nation's largest city, New York City, more than double in size due to the consolidation with Brooklyn, becoming in the process the first U.S. city to record a population growth of over three million — Brooklyn was previously the 4th largest city in the United States on its own.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Oversight of the statistics was by Frederick Howard Wines and Walter F.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1900 census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Statistician Frederick Ludwig Hoffman criticized the conduct of the census.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] The original census enumeration sheets were microfilmed by the Census Bureau in the 1940s, after which the original sheets were destroyed.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Several organizations also host images of the microfilmed census online, and digital indices.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1900 census are freely available through IPUMS.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-census] Location of 50 largest cities by population in the United States in 1900, on a map of the modern United States.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1900 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 6, 1900, as part of the 1900 United States presidential election.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Voters chose nine representatives, or electors, to the Electoral College, who voted for the President and Vice President.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Representative and 1896 Democratic presidential nominee William Jennings Bryan, over the Republican nominee, President William McKinley.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Bryan won South Carolina by a landslide margin of 85.92% in this rematch of the 1896 presidential election.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] This would be the last election when the Republican Party won any county in South Carolina until Dwight D.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Eisenhower in 1952, and the last when any county voted against the Democrats until Dixiecrat Strom Thurmond carried every county except Anderson and Spartanburg in 1948.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Bryan had previously won South Carolina against McKinley four years earlier and would later win the state again in 1908 against William Howard Taft.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1900-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Additionally, between 1900 and 1940, South Carolina gave at least 90% of the vote to the Democratic candidate, the longest streak for any state, even including D.C.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The **1904 United States presidential election in South Carolina** took place on November 8, 1904, as part of the 1904 United States presidential election.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina voted for the Democratic nominee, former Chief Judge of New York Court of Appeals Alton B.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Parker, over the Republican nominee, President Theodore Roosevelt.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Parker won South Carolina by a landslide margin of 90.74 percentage points.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Parker indeed won Hampton, Fairfield and Georgetown Counties unanimously due to the nearly complete disfranchisement of the black majority that was the Republican Party's sole support in the state.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] With 95.36% of the popular vote, South Carolina would be Parker's strongest victory in terms of percentage of the popular vote.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/1904-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Parker became the first presidential candidate to sweep every county in South Carolina.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In the colonial era the area that is now Aiken County was part of Edgefield and Orangeburgh Districts.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The majority of the population were immigrant farmers.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Most of whom were from the rural parts of Lincolnshire, England; however, very few were from the town of Lincoln.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Virtually all of the farmers from Lincolnshire came to the colony as indentured servants in the 1730s and 1740s.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] However, by the 1750s, almost all of the Lincolnshire settlers in what is now Aiken County were living on their own private land, almost exclusively engaging in subsistence agriculture on smallholding farms.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Many immigrants also came from the rural eastern half of the English county of Nottinghamshire.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Specifically, many indentured servants came from the towns of Newark-on-Trent, Winthorpe, Coddington, Balderton, Kelham and Farndon.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] These settlers also settled on lands in between the Savannah River in the west and the towns of Berlin and Jones Crossroads in the east, all arriving in what has since become Aiken County in the 1740s.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] This population referred to themselves as "Ulstermen" and "Irish Presbyterians" but were known in the colonies as "Scots-Irish" settlers, though this was not a term they self-applied.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The area that has since become Aiken County had a significantly high number of first generation British immigrants who fought for the Patriot cause in the revolutionary war.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Both Aiken County and its county seat of Aiken are named after William Aiken (1779–1831), the first president of the South Carolina Railroad Company.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Aiken County was organized during the Reconstruction era in 1871 from portions of Barnwell, Edgefield, Lexington, and Orangeburg counties.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Prince Rivers, a freedman and state legislator from Edgefield County, had been a leader in the United States Colored Troops.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] He was named to head the commission that drew the new county's boundary lines.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] He was dubbed "The Black Prince" by local newspapers, including the *Edgefield Advertiser.* He also led the commission that selected the site of Aiken County's present-day courthouse.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Other freedmen who were part of the founding of the county were Samuel J.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Lee, speaker of the state House and the first black man admitted to the South Carolina Bar; and Charles D.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Hayne, a free man of color from one of Charleston's elite families.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Political tensions kept rising in South Carolina during the 1870s, especially around elections.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In the months before the 1876 elections, Aiken County was one of the areas to suffer white paramilitary Red Shirts attacks and violence directed against black Republicans to suppress the black vote.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Between the Hamburg Massacre in July and several days of rioting in September in Ellenton, more than 100 black men were killed by white paramilitary groups in this county.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In the late 19th century, the county became a popular winter refuge for affluent Northerners, who built luxury housing.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The county remains popular with horse trainers and professional riders because mild winters allow lengthy training seasons.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In the 1950s, Aiken County (along with the nearby counties of Allendale and Barnwell) was chosen as the location for storage and production of nuclear materials and various fissile materials, now known as the Savannah River Site.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Ellenton, South Carolina was acquired and its buildings demolished for its development of this plant.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Its residents and businesses were moved north about eight miles to New Ellenton, and about 5 miles south to the town of Jackson just outside the entrance to the Savannah River Site, Developed during Cold War tensions, the facility is scheduled for decommissioning of various parts of the site.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] It is the fourth-largest county in South Carolina by land area.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, there were 168,808 people in 69,450 households, including 43,932 families residing in the county.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The median age was 42.3 years; 21.3% of residents were under the age of 18 and 20.9% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 91.9 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.8 males age 18 and over.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 65.2% White, 23.6% Black or African American, 0.4% American Indian and Alaska Native, 1.1% Asian, 0.1% Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander, 3.4% from some other race, and 6.2% from two or more races.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Hispanic or Latino residents of any race comprised 6.8% of the population.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] 63.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 37.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] There were 69,450 households in the county, of which 27.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 29.8% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] About 28.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 12.4% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] There were 76,923 housing units, of which 9.7% were vacant.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Among occupied housing units, 73.2% were owner-occupied and 26.8% were renter-occupied.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.5% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.1%.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] At the 2010 census, there were 160,099 people, 64,253 households, and 43,931 families living in the county.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The population density was 149.5 inhabitants per square mile (57.7/km2).
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] There were 72,249 housing units at an average density of 67.5 per square mile (26.1/km2).
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 69.6% white, 24.6% black or African American, 0.8% Asian, 0.4% American Indian, 2.6% from other races, and 1.9% from two or more races.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 4.9% of the population.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In terms of ancestry, 20.6% were American, 10.0% were English, 9.9% were German, and 8.6% were Irish.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Of the 64,253 households, 31.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.3% were married couples living together, 14.4% had a female householder with no husband present, 31.6% were non-families, and 26.9% of all households were made up of individuals.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.45 and the average family size was 2.96.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the county was $44,468 and the median income for a family was $57,064.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $44,436 versus $33,207 for females.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $24,172.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] About 13.4% of families and 16.6% of the population were below the poverty line, including 23.7% of those under age 18 and 13.3% of those age 65 or over.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] At the 2000 census, there were 142,552 people, 55,587 households, and 39,411 families living in the county.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The population density was 133 inhabitants per square mile (51/km2).
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] There were 61,987 housing units at an average density of 58 per square mile (22/km2).
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 71.37% White, 25.56% Black or African American, 0.40% Native American, 0.63% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, and 1.18% from two or more races.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] 2.12% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] 22.0% were of American, 9.7% English, 8.4% German and 7.9% Irish ancestry according to Census 2000.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] There were 55,587 households, out of which 33.10% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 53.30% were married couples living together, 13.80% had a female householder with no husband present, and 29.10% were non-families.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] 25.20% of all households were made up of individuals, and 9.20% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.53 and the average family size was 3.03.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In the county, the population was spread out, with 26.20% under the age of 18, 8.80% from 18 to 24, 28.90% from 25 to 44, 23.30% from 45 to 64, and 12.80% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females, there were 92.90 males.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.20 males.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the county was $37,889, and the median income for a family was $45,769.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $36,743 versus $23,810 for females.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $18,772.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] About 10.60% of families and 13.80% of the population were below the poverty line, including 18.90% of those under age 18 and 12.50% of those age 65 or over.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Gary Bunker is the Chairman of the Aiken County Council.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Aiken County was one of the first counties in South Carolina to break away from a "Solid South" voting pattern.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] It has gone Republican in every presidential election since 1956.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] It even rejected southern Democrats such as Lyndon Johnson of Texas, Jimmy Carter of Georgia, Bill Clinton of Arkansas or Al Gore of Tennessee.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Carter is the last Democrat to manage even 40 percent of the county's vote.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] However, it has trended more liberal in recent years, giving Bob Dole in 1996 a greater proportion of the vote than Donald Trump in 2016, despite Dole losing decisively to Bill Clinton nationally, and Donald Trump winning the Electoral College 304-227.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The Republican trend runs through the local level as well.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] While conservative Democrats held most state and local offices well into the 1990s, today there are almost no elected Democrats left above the county level.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In 2022, the GDP of Aiken County was $8.6 billion (approx. $48,344 per capita).
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] In chained 2017 dollars, its real GDP was $7.1 billion (approx. $42,060 per capita).
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Between 2021 and 2024, the unemployment rate has fluctuated around 3%.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] As of April 2024, some of the largest employers in the county include Aiken Regional Medical Center, Bridgestone, Hubbell Incorporated, Kimberly-Clark, Savanah River Nuclear Solutions (SRNS), Shaw Industries, UPS, and Walmart.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] The only school district covering sections of the county is Aiken County School District, which covers the majority of the county.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] A portion of the county is not in any school district, and the 2010 U.S. census stated that this portion was in "School District Not Defined".
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] That undefined portion corresponds with the Savannah River Site.
[src:aiken-county-south-carolina/aiken-county-south-carolina] Aiken Technical College and University of South Carolina Aiken are located in Aiken County.
